### 1. One-Line Summary
* Rozena is the easier, more forgiving, more stable all-round offensive rubber, while Vega Pro is the spinnier, sharper, higher-performance option for players with better timing and stronger acceleration.

### 2. Head-to-Head Breakdown
* **Speed & Gears:**
    * **Low Impact:** Rozena is livelier and easier to use on soft touch and medium contact. It gives more immediate pace without requiring a big swing.
    * **Top End:** Vega Pro has the higher ceiling when you swing hard. It rewards fuller acceleration with more penetrating power.
    * **Linearity:** Vega Pro is more linear and predictable as you increase effort. Rozena is more damped and “managed,” which makes it easier but slightly less transparent at the top end.

* **Spin Mechanics:**
    * **Opening Loop:** Vega Pro is better for heavy opening loops, especially against backspin, because it bites the ball more aggressively and transfers more rotation.
    * **Max Spin:** Vega Pro produces more maximum spin overall. Rozena has good spin, but it is clearly tuned more for consistency than for peak spin output.
    * **Topsheet Grip:** Vega Pro has the grippier, more direct topsheet behavior. Rozena grips well, but its design prioritizes forgiveness over raw bite.

* **Flight Path (Throw Angle):**
    * **Arc Height:** Rozena generally gives a slightly higher, safer arc in normal rallying. Vega Pro’s arc is still medium-high, but it feels more direct and demanding when the timing is off.
    * **Safety:** Rozena is safer for general topspin exchanges and recovery shots. Vega Pro is safer only when your technique is engaged and the contact is confident.

* **Feel & Feedback:**
    * **Sensation:** Rozena feels softer, more muted, and more cushioned. Vega Pro feels firmer, crisper, and more explicit in its feedback.
    * **Dwell:** Rozena gives a slightly longer, easier sense of holding the ball. Vega Pro’s dwell is more “active” and technique-dependent rather than automatically forgiving.

* **Control & Short Game:**
    * **Sensitivity:** Rozena is less sensitive to incoming spin and easier to manage in serve receive. Vega Pro is more reactive, so it demands cleaner touch.
    * **Touch Play:** Rozena is better for controlled pushes, short drops, and simple placement under pressure. Vega Pro can be very precise, but only if your hand is disciplined.

* **Blocking & Countering:**
    * **Passive Block:** Rozena is more stable and forgiving on passive blocks. It absorbs pace better and keeps the ball on the table more easily.
    * **Active Counter:** Vega Pro is stronger for punchier counters and more dangerous active backhand or close-to-table exchanges when the player is proactive.

### 3. The Recommendation
* **Choose Rozena if:**
    * You want the easier rubber overall with a bigger safety margin.
    * You value control, spin tolerance, and consistency more than maximum spin and power.
    * You are an intermediate player, a developing advanced player, or someone who prefers stability on both wings.
    * You rely a lot on blocking, controlled topspin, placement, and safe rallying.

* **Choose Vega Pro if:**
    * You can generate your own acceleration and want a higher performance ceiling.
    * You want stronger opening loops, heavier spin, and more direct feedback.
    * You are a solid intermediate-to-advanced attacker who can handle a firmer, more demanding response.
    * You prefer a rubber that rewards active technique more than passive safety.
